english:
  title: Preface to a Poem on Reverend Beopgyeong's Journey to Mount Geumgang
  author: Lee Seungso
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Nations dot the realm between heaven and earth like scattered millet grains. Yet our kingdom stands alone in the east where the sun rises, while the Indian lands lie at the western edge where it sets. From our shores to those distant kingdoms spans countless thousands of miles—distances that neither ships nor carts nor human feet can traverse, beyond even the reach of sight and sound. And yet the name of our Mount Geumgang has blazed across the scriptures of the Buddhist teachers in those far lands. This is because the Buddhas and World-Honored Ones, with their penetrating wisdom, perceive the great cosmos whole. They recognized that this mountain alone gathers the sublime essence of all under heaven, standing as the supreme blessed realm above the world of Jambudvipa. Thus they did not merely proclaim it through the Buddha's own lips, but inscribed it upon sacred leaves for all generations to witness. From ancient times to now, countless souls have heard its name and yearned with burning hearts to glimpse it once before death claimed them. Yet those blessed to be born in our land need only lean upon their staffs and walk to see with joy the Mountain King itself—to contemplate the diamond's meaning and awaken pure faith in their hearts, binding themselves to grace in this life and planting seeds of goodness for ages to come. And yet some, born within mere tens or hundreds of li, able to depart at dawn and arrive by dusk without the burden of provisions or blistered feet, have never gone at all. What manner of heart is this? What heart is mine?

    One day Reverend Beopgyeong came to my dwelling in Nansanri, bearing a poem, and spoke thus: "I once wandered Mount Geumgang and beheld its thousand peaks vying in beauty—like jade pillars set upon drifts of eternal snow. The grasses and trees, the streams and stones gleamed in crystalline wonder. Winds and moonlight, mist and rosy clouds breathed forth such luminous purity that all touching eye and entering ear became clarified radiance and harmonious song, sufficient to wash away worldly dust and kindle profound awakening. Small wonder the Buddha-lands name it supreme among all under heaven. Now I go again to explore what remained unvisited before, hoping to glimpse enlightenment in a single night's meditation. I beg you: write a few words to kindle my purpose, which I shall present as introduction to the venerable masters dwelling in those mountains."

    Alas! I am bound by the chains of this world. How often do I crane my neck toward the east, yearning for one glimpse that never comes? How could I remain silent as the Reverend departs?

    I have heard that in Buddhist teaching, the diamond symbolizes the true nature and Buddha-nature itself. This nature—seeking it in the past reveals no beginning; tracing it to the future shows no end. Though mountains and earth may crumble to dust, this nature endures eternal, untouched by the fires of cosmic destruction. Thus the Diamond Mountain King spoken of is not in the mountain itself, but within us. Should one illuminate one's own mind and awaken to one's true nature, piercing through ten thousand phenomena to reveal the naked truth—then the mountain's height and grandeur become the jeweled body manifest, and the eighty-four thousand dharma-gates become the mountain's myriad valleys and thousand peaks. There is no need to seek far afield; one's own nature becomes the perfect teacher. To do otherwise—fleeing noise to seek silence, abandoning the world to wander alone—is mere delusion, unescaping the eternal reproach: "seeing the mountain, forgetting the Way." When the Reverend returns to the mountain and poses this question to the venerable masters there, surely one will smile.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jambudvipa (閻浮界): In Buddhist cosmology, the southern continent of the four great continents surrounding Mount Meru, typically understood to represent the human world.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The eighty-four thousand dharma-gates (八萬四千法門): A Buddhist term for the infinite teachings and paths to enlightenment.'
  - key: ''
    value: The final reference to "seeing the mountain, forgetting the Way" alludes to a Buddhist verse attributed to the Tang master Yongjia Xuanjue, warning against mistaking external beauty for spiritual truth.
